column52: Delivery of Youth Detention Accommodation - Lot 3 Medway
column53:
There are currently three Secure Training Centres (STCs) in England which provide Youth Detention Accommodation. They are privately operated centres that accommodate younger and/or more vulnerable boys, girls and young mothers between the ages of 12-17. The existing contracts for Medway and Rainsbrook STCs are due to expire in the first half of 2016. The contracts relevant to this notice have been put in place by the Authority to continue the provision of Youth Detention Accommodation beyond the current contracts. This is due to a continued demand for this type of provision to accommodate and rehabilitate the most high risk children and young people demonstrating complex needs. The contracts aim to contribute to the delivery of the following strategic aims:
• to improve educational engagement and attainment in youth custody by allowing greater innovation in delivery
• to contribute, through this increased focus on education, to reduced re-offending by young people leaving custody
• to reduce the overall cost of youth custody, focusing in particular on driving down the costs of the most expensive provision

column52: 588 Dynamic Vapour Absorption
column53: Dynamic Vapour Sorption (DVS) or Dynamic Vapour Absorption (DVA) is a technique that measures how quickly and how much of a solvent is absorbed by a particular sample.  The sample can be solid or liquid and the technique is used in many different industries to quantify, for example, water uptake by powders and plasticizing of polymers with solvents.  Understanding these properties greatly enhances both processing capability and measurement of application properties.   The ability to understand these properties will greatly enhance the capability of the National Formulation Centre

column52: Demountable Swimming Pool
column53:
DEMOUNTABLE SWIMMING POOL

RIVERMEAD LEISURE CENTRE, RICHFIELD AVENENUE, READING

Reading Borough Council is seeking contractors to provide design and build services to construct a demountable swimming facility at Rivermead Leisure Centre, Richfield Avenue, Reading, RG1 8ED. 

An existing swimming pool in the Reading is reaching the end of its viable life and a demountable pool is required by October 2017 as a temporary replacement whilst a permanent solution is sought.

The demountable swimming facility will be an extension to the rear of the existing leisure pool and will be managed by Greenwich Leisure Ltd (GLL) who operates the leisure centre on behalf of the Council.

The proposed layout of the facility is to include:

•	25m*10.5m*1.2m training pool
•	10m*13m*0.9m teaching pool
•	Changing accommodation
•	Associated plant and storage

The Centre is located near the River Thames and was built in 1987 on the site of a disused 1970’s domestic tip. Recent ground investigations have recommended the use of piling as part of the foundation strategy to allow for the floodplain and landfill issues associated with the site.

Currently the scheme is at Feasibility stage and we are looking for contractors who believe they are capable of providing a full design and build service and are interested in carrying out all the associated design and construction works to open a demountable swimming facility by October 2017. The total project value including all design fees, construction and fit-out costs is £1.8million and we are looking for suitable contractors to provide the demountable swimming facility within this financial envelope.

Contractors who believe they are capable of fulfilling these requirements should notify Reading Borough Council of their interest in writing. To register your interest, provide a brief summary of which procurement frameworks you are registered to together with your organisational experience and capability in designing and constructing similar demountable swimming pools. This will be in the form of no more than two sides of A4 (additional PDF attachments will not be read) and sent no later than 5pm on Wednesday 20th April 2016 using the In-Tend e-tendering system

The Council intends to use the information supplied to assess whether suitable contractors exist to meet the Council’s requirements to provide a demountable swimming pool extension at Rivermead Leisure Complex by October 2017. If the Council decides there is sufficient interest from contractors it may decide to proceed with a procurement exercise through further advertisement to formally invite tenders. The Council does not commit to enter into a formal procurement exercise at this stage.

Additional information: In order to respond to this opportunity you will need to register on In-Tend select "view details" then "express interest".

column52: Rugby GP Out of Hours Provision –  NHS Coventry and Rugby CCG
column53:
This is a Prior Information Notice published by NHS Arden & Greater East Midlands Commissioning Support Unit (AGCSU) on behalf of NHS Coventry and Rugby Clinical Commissioning Group (the CCG). 

NHS Coventry and Rugby CCG are in the process of developing an Out of Hospital Integrated Urgent Care Model of Care for Coventry and Rugby, and expressions of interest are invited for the provision of GP Out of Hours Services for the Rugby population only, for an interim period whilst this work is completed.

The contract will be let for a contract term of 11 months with the option to extend up to a maximum of 6 months if required by the CCG. Services to commence 1st November 2016. 

Estimated budget is £690,000 for 11 months.  

The CCG would like to assess current market appetite to provide this service. The market response to this advert will determine the next steps. The CCG intends to use a Most Capable Provider Assessment subject to receipt of no more than 2 Expressions of Interest from the market.  
To register your interest in supplying this service, please complete the form online through the Arden GEM Bravo e-tendering portal -ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk. 

To complete the form online:

i)	Register on the portal at: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk (registration and use of the website is free of charge). 

ii)	Express interest by 
a) logging-in to the ARDEN GEMCSU e-Tendering portal 
b) selecting response to advert and PQQ
c) select Open Access PQQ
d) search for and access listing related to this contract and view details
e) click on Express Interest link 

iii)	Once you have expressed interest, access the My PQQs page where you can complete the questionnaire. 

Please note that this is not a PQQ, we are using this functionality within the Bravo portal to communicate with interested parties. 

Closing date for registering interest is 13th April 2016 at 12 noon. 

Please note that after this deadline participation cannot be guaranteed. 

A service specification for this service is to follow. 

It should be noted that this is not a procurement exercise and participating organisations are responsible for their own costs. 

The services to which this notice relates fall within Part B of Schedule 3, Part 10 of the Public Services Contracts Regulations 2006 (as amended) ("the Regulations"). 

Neither the publication of this notice nor the employment of neither any particular terminology nor any other indication shall be taken to mean that the contracting authorities intend to hold themselves bound by any of the Regulations save those applicable to the procurement of Part B services.

column52: The Textile Waste Contract
column53:
Devon County Council, as the Waste Disposal Authority works in partnership with the District Councils and Unitary Authorities through Devon Authorities Waste Reduction and Recycling Committee (DAWRRC). DAWRRC members are working together to achieve a 65 % recycling rate by 2025/26 and achieve best value in the provision of the sale of recyclable materials collected from householders and from recycling facilities throughout Devon. The participant DAWRRC members at the Contract's Commencement will be East Devon District Council, Exeter City Council, Mid Devon District Council, North Devon Council, Teignbridge District Council, South Hams District Council, West Devon Borough Council and Torbay Council. The Service is being procured for the benefit and potential future participation of other DAWRRC members, should they choose to join the Contract.
This Contract is for the provision, maintenance of clothing and textile banks at various locations specified in Appendix 2 of the ITT, collection of material deposited in the banks by the public, as well as collecting the material stockpiled as part of the kerbside collection schemes provided by the participating DAWRRC members.


Additional information: The Tendering period for this contract has expired. This is a contract award notice to the successful bidder.
Service entails placement of textile bank at various locations in the County of Devon and subsequent collection of waste deposited in the bank by the public

column52: CF51 Invitation to Tender for Advisory Services in Respect of the Investment Sale / Funding of the Northgate Development , Chester - CH1
column53:
Cheshire West and Chester Borough Council (?the Council?) is looking to appoint an investment agent to advise it on the sale/ funding of Northgate, Chester.  This is a two stage instruction that will be awarded based on a one off procurement and appointment process. Northgate will be the prime retail and leisure centre in Chester with a lot size in the range 200million -300million. Northgate is a retail led mixed use scheme incorporating residential, hotel, market, offices and cinema. The scheme is currently pre construction with a phased completion targeted through 2018-2021. The high level programme is provided at Schedule 2. The scheme has an estimated ERV of 15million. The Council requires an investment agent to advise on all options available for the forward sale/ funding of the scheme. The Council will require an investment agent to provide initial strategic advice on the options for funding/ sale within 8 weeks of appointment. The successful bidder will then act as formal agent for the sale/ funding of the scheme, subject to satisfactory performance and scheme progression.

Additional information: Cheshire West and Chester Borough Council is looking to procure Advisory Services in respoect of the Investment Sale / Funding of the Northgate Development, Chester.
This contract is being procured using an e-tendering system called ?The Chest?. If you are not currently registered, go to the following and click the ?Register Free? box:
https://www.the-chest.org.uk/
Once registered go to:
https://procontract.due-north.com/Opportunities/Index?resetFilter=True
You will be able to search via the ?Organisation? drop-down menu for Cheshire West and Chester tenders. Select this particular opportunity from the list and register interest; you will then be able to find further information and access the Invitation to Tender (ITT) document and any additional Information. The closing date for receipt of ITT submissions via ?The Chest? is on 03.05.2016 (12:00).
You are advised to express an interest and subsequently access and start your ITT Response and meet the deadline, which is absolute.
Once the closing date has passed, the evaluation process will begin. It is estimated that a decision will not be made until 10.05.2016.
The guidance notes provided with the ITT document on the Chest show an estimated timetable to assist you. The ITT and any subsequent additional information will be available to download from ?The Chest?. It is your responsibility to download the ITT document from ?The Chest?.

column52: SCC HA Property Scope Research
column53:
Surrey County Council would like to procure research and consulting services for hard to reach properties ie.households including flats, apartments or maisonettes.

Background:
According to the 2011 ONS census, more than one in five Surrey households (21%) live in a flat, apartment or maisonette. This includes purpose built blocks of flats, converted or shared houses or accommodation in a commercial building (eg over a shop). This equates to nearly 95,000 households. 

Surrey County Council (SCC) is working on behalf of the Surrey Waste Partnership (SWP). The SWP have indentified six key problem areas that are preventing SWP from achieving the requirements of its joint strategy, one of these being hard to reach properties. For the purpose of this project, households including flats, apartments or maisonettes will all be classified under the term hard to reach properties.

Work to tackle the issues of low recycling performance at hard to reach properties has been carried out across Surrey, but the extent of this has varied across the districts and boroughs. A full understanding of the work that has already taken place and of the data and information held by districts and boroughs is needed to inform a programme of work for a future SWP hard to reach properties team.

Aim:
•	Appoint consultants to conduct a scoping exercise that gathers information about hard to reach properties and provides recommendations for future work.
Objectives
•	Carry out desk based data gathering and interviews to collate information from the SWP district and boroughs about their hard to reach properties.
•	Following the information and data gathering, collate and report information on SWP’s hard to reach properties.
•	Identify the high priority sites that need immediate attention.
•	Provide recommendations for future improvement work at Surrey’s hard to reach properties.

Outcome:
This scoping exercise is the first of a three part approach to conducting an inventory of our hard to reach properties and implementing improvements. The information gathered from the exercise will be used to inform the recruitment and work of a specific hard to reach properties team. Following the scoping exercise the newly formed team will use the results of the scoping exercise to:
1.	Build a plan of work and prioritise the most hard to reach properties.
2.	Carry out site surveys for properties to identify improvements that can be made.
3.	Implement tailored service changes and communication improvements.

Timeframe:
SWP are looking for the scoping activity to be completed by the end of June 2016.


Additional information: This tender is to be completed electronically using the SE Shared Services Procurement eSourcing portal.

http://www.sesharedservices.org.uk/esourcing

The SE Shared Services eSourcing portal provides a web-based tool that provides a simple, secure and efficient means for managing tendering and quotation activities reducing the time and effort required for both buyers and Potential Bidders. column52: Older Workers Research using the Workplace Employment Relations Survey (WERS)
column53:
The Minister for Pensions will be launching an employer driven national strategy on Fuller Working Lives. It is crucial we develop a strong understanding of
(i)	The link between employer policies and practices, and the employment of older workers in order to identify, promote and potentially implement evidence backed policies to recruit and retain older workers in the workplace. 
(ii)	the impact of older workers on workplace performance to effectively engage with    employers 
The Fuller Working Lives Background Evidence Review considered a number of data sources (including the Labour Force Survey) and a wide range of external research pieces to bring together the current evidence base related to older workers.  The evidence base is largely descriptive and focuses on the reasons that older workers fall out of the labour market and the barriers they face in regaining employment.  There are clear gaps around ‘what works’ to keep older workers in work and the benefits to employers in retaining and recruiting older workers. 
Understanding these questions should bring a step change to the evidence base for Fuller Working Lives (FWL). In particular this research should enhance the evidence on the role of employers and impacts of older workers and has great potential to inform policy direction in this area to improve productivity and contribute to full employment.

column52: Dietetics and Healthy Weight
column53: Medway Council are seeking to commission an external provider or freelance dietitian to become part of its successful tier 3 adult weight management programme. The Public Health Team have delivered the Tipping the Balance programme for over 7 years with a multi-disciplinary group of professionals providing 18 months of support for referred clients. The programme goals are to;  Reduce bodyweight by 5% or above  Increase physical activity levels and healthy eating  Increase confidence and self esteem Professionals working within the service include specialist weight management nurses, counselling and psychotherapy support and physical activity specialists. The service is looking to recruit a dietetic provider on a commissioned contract basis, to add to the skill mix of the MDT. They will be required to provide the specialists dietetic input, building on the nutritional input and healthy eating advice the clients already receive and contribute to the broader outcomes of the tier 3 team. The provider will be expected to support a cohort of the 600 clients that are active on the programme, providing specialist dietetic support, in order to help the clients achieve their weight loss goals. They will be expected to work with the client over a series of appointments setting personalised goals, advising on diet changes and using behaviour change skills to maximise the effectiveness of their input. The provider must provide evidence of how they are meeting industry standards and best practise guidance throughout the duration of the contract. The exact content of the dietetic support sessions, the number of clients that will be supported each year, and how many sessions each client will be invited to attend, must be stated by the potential provider during the recruitment process. Medway Council is seeking to recruit a provider who offer the best balance between cost effectiveness and outcomes for the client. The tender process will be in 2 stages, with a written response required in stage 1 and the highest scoring organisations progressing to an interview stage, that will be held on 7th December 2015. For further information about the tender process, or to register for additional information about the service, all providers must register with the Kent Business Portal. This site will hold the full tender document, detailing the recruitment process, scoring criteria, full service specification and key performance indicators that the provider will undertake. This is an exciting opportunity for a dietetic provider or free-lancer to join a highly motivated, forward thinking and successful service, for a 3 year contract, and we welcome interest from all providers who feel they can add value to the tier 3 service and clients that they support.

column52: Assessing the effects of Higher Level Stewardship options on lowland heathlands and its priority species, with a particular focus on grazing effects
column53:
Evidence Programme Ref 22257
 To deliver the following objectives:
 
a) To produce a methodology to determine the extent to which HLS has (a) delivered an improvement in lowland heathland condition; (b) been appropriately targeted. This will be achieved by using a combination of field survey, and comparison with earlier survey material. 
b) To use the developed methodology on an appropriate sample of HLS agreements on lowland heathlands to assess the most common management options (grazing, cutting, burning and chemical control of bracken/scrub), with particular focus on grazing, and evaluate their success in terms of progress towards, or achievement of Favourable Condition (FC) for the habitat by comparing them with the condition pre-agreement. The sample should ideally include a counterfactual element, to assess management approaches taken without HLS agreement;
 c) To assess (i) how changes in the attributes and (ii) features required to achieve FC impact on the associated species (e.g. the provision of bare ground results in more populations of solitary wasps).
 d) To evaluate the overall effectiveness of the HLS scheme thus far for Lowland Heathlands, using the outputs from objectives a, b and c, noting individual successful and unsuccessful interventions and the reasons for them.

column51: AUD10075 INNOVATING FOR GROWTH SCALE UPS PROGRAMME - PRODUCT & SERVICE INNOVATION MODULE
column52: AUD10075 Innovating For Growth Scale Ups Programme - Product & Service Innovation Module
column53:
The British Library’s Business & IP Centre is designed to support small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) and entrepreneurs from that first spark of inspiration to successfully launching and growing a business.

With funding support from the European Regional Development Fund, the Centre launched the ‘Innovating for Growth’ programme in late 2011 to focus on providing support to growth businesses, as opposed to start ups. Innovating for Growth – Phase 1 was completed in December 2015. Innovating for Growth - Phase 2 is due to start service delivery in May 2016, subject to final funding approval.

The ‘Innovating for Growth - Scale-ups’ programme aims to use the Centre’s unique resources and expertise to help high-growth businesses scale up, through developing new products and services and entering new markets. Each SME completes a number of face-to-face support modules through a combination of one-to-one meetings and workshops, which are tailored to the SME’s needs.

The face-to-face support, combined with practical workshops, is designed to accelerate each SMEs progress to the next stage. The Business & IP Centre’s information professionals alongside selected delivery partners will help each SME to put together a growth strategy and plan for their business, as well as identifying the workshops and one-to-one’s each SME will need to attend to hone their business knowledge and skills.

The module available for tender is: 

AUD10075 Product & Service Innovation Module

The Product & Service Innovation module will be conducted through one-to-one meetings.

The successful bidder will help each SME on the programme to develop a successful and sustainable growth plan, through helping them optimise their business processes. Through optimising business processes, this module will help SMEs successfully bring their new products or services to market.  

This module will focus on the left side of the Business Model Canvas, which includes elements where enhancements are likely to have the greatest impact on the client’s ability to successfully commercialise product/service ideas.

If you are interested in tendering for this opportunity please browse to www.bl.bravosolution.co.uk and click on the View current opportunities and notices link for further details.

column51: HQIP HCA 2000 Perinatal Mortality Review Tool
column52: HQIP HCA 2000 Perinatal Mortality Review Tool
column53:
The Healthcare Quality Improvement Partnership (HQIP) has been requested to commission a Perinatal Mortality Review Tool on behalf of the Department of Health in England, and the Scottish and Welsh
Governments.
The overarching aim of this programme is the development and maintenance of a web-based tool to implement standardised perinatal mortality reviews across NHS maternity and neonatal units in England, Scotland and Wales and provide training and on-going IT support for users.
The programme will comprise:
1. The development and maintenance of a web-based tool to facilitate the introduction of standardised perinatal
mortality reviews across NHS maternity and neonatal units in England, Scotland and Wales. This tool will help clinicians to review the circumstances and care leading up to and surrounding each stillbirth and neonatal deaths in a systematic way, identify any sub-optimal care factors and then based on responses to the questions in the data-set, provide a grading of care, creation of a local action plan and allow organisations to identify themes across multiple cases to facilitate organisational change to reduce risk
2. Training in use of the tool and on-going IT support for users
3. Annual analysis of UK and country-specific wide data and reporting on themes and trends.The contract for the programme will run for three years, with opportunities for the duration of the contract to be
re-assessed at the end of each year subject to the availability of funding and an assessment by the Independent Advisory Group on the quality of delivery of the programme

column52: Adult Community Health Services - Guildford and Waverley
column53:
NHS Guildford and Waverley CCG wishes to commission Adult Community Health Services for the adult GP registered population to ensure high quality and innovative service provision across Guildford and Waverley. 
Community services are intended as an alternative to hospital-based outpatient services where non-complex acute and chronic conditions can be seen for clinical assessment, diagnostics and treatment in a community setting. This is in line with GWCCG’s strategic commissioning intentions  to ensure that high quality care is delivered as close to the patient’s home as is appropriate. 
GWCCG has a clear vision for the development of a comprehensive and fully integrated model of health and care provision to our local population. Central to this vision is the development of excellent integrated community services, working under the leadership of Primary Care to provide a holistic health and care response genuinely tailored to the needs of a specific individual. Our new model of care, which will continue to evolve from 2017 onwards, focuses on the creation of an organised, coordinated and effective out of hospital provider environment that is seen as the main conduit for meeting a person’s health and care needs. 
Through this procurement process, NHS Guildford and Waverley CCG is seeking a provider to deliver ‘out of hospital’ services that will work with the CCG and other key partners to deliver the highest quality healthcare for the population of Guildford and Waverley.
As the NHS continues through the process of change, GWCCG wish to work with providers who have the capability to embrace change and continually support and motivate their workforce towards innovative service delivery. The transformation of our community services is a key step in achieving this model of care. 
Historically, community services have been provided by a large number of fragmented and separate teams across the primary, acute, community and social sectors. It is our ambition to move away from this paradigm by instead creating integrated community health and care services that are capable of delivering a flexible and wide ranging service response based on clinical need, whenever it is required.
GW CCG is holding a bidder briefing event on 13 April 2016. Details of how to register to attend are attached to this notice.

Additional information: Organisations interesting in bidding to provide this service will need to register on the EU Supply e-tendering portal https://nhssbs.eu-supply.com and search for tender ID 23436.
